  "meta": {
    "title": "Return to driving following first-ever seizure",
    "authors": "Brown JWL, Lawn ND, Lee J, et al.",
    "journal": "Journal of Neurology, Neurosurgery &amp; Psychiatry",
    "year": 2015,
    "doi": "10.1136/jnnp-2013-307529",
    "outcome": "When is it safe to return to driving following first-ever seizure?",
    "clinical_utility": "The risk of recurrence following a first-ever seizure is 40-50%, warranting driving restriction during the early period of highest risk. This restriction must be balanced against the occupational, educational and social limitations that result from patients being ineligible to drive. The recommended duration of non-driving after a first seizure varies widely between jurisdictions, influenced by various factors including the community perception of an acceptable relative level of risk for an accident (the accident risk ratio; ARR).",
    "pmid": "24769470"
